For Natural Gas Transportation Services Pursuant to 18 C.F.R. Section 284.224

1. PRELIMINARY STATEMENT 1.1 Northern States Power Company, a Minnesota corporation (NSPM or “Transporter”), is a public utility and natural gas local distribution company operating within the State of North Dakota, including purchasing, selling, and distributing natural gas for retail to residential and commercial customers and transporting natural gas to industrial, commercial, and residential customers, all of which is subject to the jurisdiction of the North Dakota Public Service Commission under Title 49 of the North Dakota Century Code. Using portions of its natural gas local distribution pipeline system (the “LDC System”) that are located wholly within the State of North Dakota, pursuant to approval by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (“FERC”) pursuant to Section 284.224 of FERC’s regulations (18 C.F.R. § 284.22), Northern States Power Company – Minnesota, 188 FERC ¶ 62,032 (2024). NSPM will engage in the transportation of natural gas from NSPM’s town border station at VGTGrand Forks, ND to an interconnection with Dakota Natural Gas Company, located at the intersection of U.S. Route 2 and County Road 3 in Larimore, North Dakota, pursuant to the following terms and conditions. 1.2 It is the policy of Transporter to consider all service requests in light of its existing commitments, pipeline design capacity, available pipeline capacity, available Receipt Point(s) and Delivery Point(s), and other factors deemed material by Transporter in its reasonable judgment. 1.3 If any conflict arises between the provisions of this Operating Statement and a Gas Transportation Service Agreement, the provisions of this Operating Statement will control with regard to such conflict. Notwithstanding any other provision that may be construed to the contrary, Transporter reserves the right to revise this Operating Statement to adopt any or all standards heretofore or hereafter adopted by the North American Energy Standards Board or to make any other revisions Transporter deems appropriate. Upon revision to this Operating Statement, Transporter will make notice thereof available to each Shipper.2. DEFINITIONS Except as otherwise specified, the following terms as used herein and in the Gas Transportation Service Agreement will be construed to have the following scope and meaning: 2.1. “Agent” means a third party who has the authority to exercise certain or all rights and/or perform certain or all obligations set forth in the Gas Transportation Service Agreement for the benefit of the Shipper(s). The Agent and the Shipper may be one and the same. 2.2. “Btu” means one (1) International Table Btu, or BtuIT, which is a unit of energy defined in the International Steam Table, where 1 BtuIT = 1055.056 joules. 2.3. “Business Day” means all non-Holiday weekdays. 2.4. “Ccf” means 100 cubic feet of gas. 2.5. “Central Clock Time” or “CCT” means Central Standard Time, except for that period when daylight savings time is in effect. During this daylight savings time period, CCT shall mean Central Daylight Time. 2.6. “Credit Rating” means, with respect to an entity on any date of determination, the rating then assigned to such entity's unsecured and senior unsubordinated long-term debt obligations (not supported by third-party credit enhancement) by Standards and Poor’s (“S&P”) or Moody's. 2.7. “Credit Support Provider" means an entity providing a Guarantee, whose lowest Credit Rating is at least BBB– by S&P or Baa3 by Moody's. 2.8. “Daily Variance Penalty” means the penalty assessed to Shipper when Shipper’s actual receipts from Transporter are more than ±5% of Shipper’s daily Nomination, as determined by comparing Shipper’s actual metered use with the volume nominated. The penalty will be assessed at $0.05 per Therm of actual receipts over ±5% of Shipper’s daily Nomination. 2.9. “Dekatherm” or “Dth” means one (1) Dth is the energy equivalent to 10 therms, or 1,000,000 Btu (1 MMBtu). One (1) therm is the energy equivalent to 100,000 Btu. 2.10. “Delivery Point(s)” means the point of interconnection between the LDC Pipeline System and the facilities of the Interconnecting Party(s) where Transporter delivers gas for the account of Shipper after transportation on the LDC Pipeline System, as specified on an Exhibit to the Gas Transportation Service Agreement. 2.11. “Electronic Bulletin Board” or “EBB” means the World Wide Web Site established and maintained by Transporter for the purpose of identifying the day-to-day procedures, communications protocols, business practices, Nominations and Imbalance management for transportation service on Transporter’s system. If there are inconsistencies between the web site and this Operating Statement, the Operating Statement shall control. 2.12. “Equivalent Quantity” means the sum of the quantities of gas, measured in dekatherms, received by Transporter for the account of Shipper at the Receipt Point(s) during any given period-of-time, after any applicable reduction for Fuel Reimbursement. The quantities of gas, measured in dekatherms, delivered at the Delivery Point(s) after transportation shall be equal to the quantities of gas received at the Receipt Point(s) for transportation, after reduction for Fuel Reimbursement. 2.13. “FERC” shall mean the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or any federal commission, agency or other governmental body or bodies succeeding to, lawfully exercising or superseding any powers which are exercisable by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. 2.14. “Firm” means transportation service that has the highest priority of transportation service offered by Transporter under this Operating Statement. 2.15. “Force Majeure” shall have the meaning provided in Section 17. 2.16. “Fuel Reimbursement” means the quantity of gas that Shipper shall be responsible for providing Transporter at the Receipt Point(s) to compensate Transporter for Shipper’s allocable share of the gas used by Transporter for fuel, and for gas lost and unaccounted for in the LDC Pipeline System, stated in terms of a percentage of the physical quantities received into the LDC Pipeline System. The Fuel Reimbursement percentage is included in the applicable pipeline commodity rates as set forth in Transporter’s currently effective Statement of Rates and as reflected in Shipper’s Gas Transportation Service Agreement, and may be discounted to reflect the relative use of the LDC Pipeline System necessary for Transporter to perform the transportation under Shipper’s Gas Transportation Service Agreement. 2.17. “Gas” or “Natural Gas” means any mixture of hydrocarbons consisting essentially of methane. These terms need not be capitalized to have this meaning. 2.18. “Gas Day” means a period of twenty-four (24) consecutive-hours beginning and ending at 9:00 a.m. CCT. The reference date for any Gas Day shall be the date at the beginning of such 24-hour period. 2.19. “Gas Transportation Service Agreement” means the agreement entered into between Transporter and Shipper providing for the transportation by Transporter of Shipper’s Gas from the Receipt Point(s) through the LDC Pipeline System to the Delivery Point(s) pursuant to this Operating Statement. 2.20. “Guarantee” means a guarantee of the obligations of Shipper which is provided by Shipper's Credit Support Provider in favor of Transporter, with such form of guarantee being acceptable to Transporter in reasonable discretion. 2.21. “Holiday” means New Year’s Day, Martin Luther King, Jr. Day, Presidents’ Day, Memorial Day, Independence Day, Labor Day, Columbus Day, Veterans Day, Thanksgiving Day, and Christmas Day. 2.22. “Imbalance” means the difference between the quantity of Shipper's Gas received by Transporter at the Receipt Point(s), less Fuel Reimbursement, and the quantity of gas delivered at the Delivery Point(s) for Shipper's account. 2.23. “Interconnecting Party” means the operator of the facilities immediately upstream of the Receipt Point(s) or the operator of the facilities immediately downstream of the Delivery Point(s). 2.24. “Interstate Pipeline” shall have the same meaning as provided in Section 2(16) of the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978, as amended, (“NGPA”) and Part 284 of the regulations of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. 2.25. “Interruptible” means transportation service provided for under this Operating Statement which is of lesser priority and quality as compared that of Firm transportation service provided under this Operating Statement. 2.26. “Interruption” means reducing, suspending or discontinuing either the receipt or delivery of gas. 2.27. “LDC Pipeline System” means the pipelines, compressor stations, regulator stations, meters, gas processing facilities and other related facilities owned by Transporter and utilized in providing transportation service. 2.28. “Master Point List” means a listing of all currently available Receipt Point(s) as provided on Transporter’s EBB. 2.29. “Maximum Daily Quantity” or “MDQ”) means the maximum daily quantity of gas expressed in Dekatherms. Transporter is obligated to transport for Shipper as set forth on an Exhibit to the Firm Gas Transportation Service Agreement. Transporter may agree from time to time to transport on an interruptible basis for Shipper, as set forth on an Exhibit to the Interruptible Gas Transportation Service Agreement. This term is used interchangeably with Maximum Daily Contract Quantity, or MDCQ, as well as Maximum Daily Transportation Quantity, or MDTQ. 2.30. “Mcf” means 1,000 cubic feet of gas. 2.31. “MMBtu” means one (1) million (1,000,000) Btu. 2.32. “Month” means the period beginning at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time on the first day of a calendar month and ending at 8:59 a.m. Central Clock time on the same day of the following calendar month. 2.33. “Nomination” means the physical Quantity of gas that a Shipper requests to transport on the Transporter’s LDC Pipeline System for a specific Gas Day. Nominations are to be adjusted to include Fuel Reimbursement and shall be made on a Dekatherm basis. 2.34. “North Dakota PSC” or “NDPSC” means the North Dakota Public Service Commission or any state commission, agency or other North Dakota governmental body or bodies succeeding to, lawfully exercising or superseding any powers which are exercisable by the North Dakota Public Service Commission. 2.35. “Party” means either Transporter or Shipper, as the case may be, and “Parties” shall mean both Transporter and Shipper, except where the reference is to the Interconnecting Party or Interconnecting Parties. 2.36. “Primary Receipt Point(s)” means Receipt Point(s) specified in the Firm Gas Transportation Service Agreement or amendments thereto as Primary Receipt Point(s) where Receiving Party is entitled to Firm Gas Transportation Service on Transporter's System. 2.37. “Receipt Point(s)” means the interconnect wherein Transporter receives gas tendered by or for the account of Shipper for transportation on Transporter’s LDC Pipeline System. Receipt Point(s) are specified in the Service Agreement or amendments thereto and/or in the Master Point List on Transporter’s EBB. 2.38. “Request for Gas Transportation Service” means a written request for transportation service submitted by any prospective Shipper as provided in this Operating Statement. 2.39. “Shipper” means the party that holds lawful right and title to the gas that is being transported, and any Party who (a) is receiving service in accordance with this Operating Statement, (b) has executed a Gas Transportation Service Agreement, or (c) has completed a request for service under Section 5 of this Operating Statement. 2.40. “Shipper’s Gas” means gas for which title is held by the Shipper under a Service Agreement. 2.41. “Therm” means 100 cubic feet (Ccf) of gas adjusted to reflect a heat content of 1,000 Btu (British thermal units) per cubic foot. 2.42. “Transporter” means Northern States Power Company, a Minnesota corporation, also sometimes referred to as “the Company.” 2.43. "Year" means a period of three hundred sixty-five (365) consecutive days or three hundred sixty-six (366) consecutive days if such period includes February 29, beginning January 1, unless otherwise specified. 3. RATE ELECTION, SERVICES, AND CHARGES 3.1 Rate Election. Transporter has elected pursuant to 18 C.F.R. § 284.123(b)(1)(ii) to use for transportation service provided under this Operating Statement the rates established under its transportation rate codes in effect from time to time for LDC service contained in its state gas tariff on file with the North Dakota PSC, which Transporter has determined covers comparable service. Specifically, the rates and charges for Firm Transportation Service under this Operating Statement, as reflected in Transporter’s Statement of Rates, shall be within the applicable range of rates for service provided by Transporter under its Rate Code 415, Large Commercial Firm Transportation Service, as part of its North Dakota Gas Rate Book – NDPSC No. 2, and the rates and charges for Interruptible Transportation Service under this Operating Statement shall be within the applicable range of rates for service by Transporter under its Rate Code 407, Large Commercial Interruptible Transportation Service, as part of its North Dakota Gas Rate Book – NDPSC No. 2, including any the applicable pipeline commodity rates under those rate codes. Notwithstanding this provision, Transporter may offer a discounted rate that varies from the maximum rate established. Transporter may from time to time file with the North Dakota PSC to change the applicable rates for transportation service under its Rate Codes 407 and 415, and, upon the effective of date of such change, may file a revised Statement of Rates reflecting such changed rates applicable to service under this Operating Statement. Transporter shall be entitled to implement such changed rates for service rendered to Shipper under this Operating Statement on their effective dates, unless otherwise provided in Shipper’s Gas Transportation Service Agreement. Nothing in this section limits Shipper's rights to contest such changes, nor limits the rights of Shipper and Transporter to provide for lawful changes in rates through the terms of the Gas Transportation Service Agreement. 3.2 Services. (a) Firm Transportation Service. Subject to this Operating Statement and the applicable Gas Transportation Service Agreement, Shipper shall cause to be delivered, and Transporter shall receive from Shipper, daily quantities of gas at the Receipt Point(s), and Transporter shall transport and deliver, and Shipper shall cause to be received, an Equivalent Quantity of gas up to Shipper’s MDQ at the Delivery Point(s), such receipts and deliveries to be as nominated by Shipper and confirmed and scheduled by Transporter pursuant to Section 6 below. Firm transportation service shall not be subject to curtailment or Interruption except as provided for in this Operating Statement. (1) All charges for Firm gas transportation service shall be as set forth in Transporter’s currently effective Statement of Rates, as adjusted from time to time. (2) The availability of Firm transportation service will be limited by Transporter's determination as to whether it has sufficient available capacity to perform the service requested by Shipper. (b) Interruptible Transportation Service. Subject to this Operating Statement and the applicable Gas Transportation Service Agreement, Shipper shall cause to be delivered, and Transporter shall receive from Shipper on an interruptible basis, daily quantities of gas at the Receipt Point(s), and Transporter shall transport and deliver on an interruptible basis, and Shipper shall cause to be received, an Equivalent Quantity of gas up to Shipper’s MDQ at the Delivery Point(s), such receipts and deliveries to be as nominated by Shipper and confirmed and scheduled by Transporter pursuant to Section 6 below. Interruptible transportation service shall be subject to curtailment and/or Interruption as provided in Section 9 of this Operating Statement. (1) All charges for Interruptible Transportation Service shall be as set forth in the currently effective Statement of Rates, as adjusted from time to time. (2) Interruptible Transportation Service is subject to availability of System capacity in Transporter’s System. Should Transporter, in its reasonable judgment, determine that adequate System capacity is unavailable, then Shipper is subject to immediate Interruption of Transportation Service. The terms of Interruptible Transportation Service provided to a Shipper, shall be as set forth in the Shipper’s Interruptible Gas Transportation Service Agreement or amendments thereto and this Statement. (3) Transporter reserves the right to not offer, not commence, or discontinue any Interruptible Transportation Service if, in Transporter’s reasonable judgment, any impairment of Firm service could result. 3.3 Fuel Reimbursement. Reimbursement for Transporter’s fuel costs is included in the applicable pipeline commodity rates as set forth in Transporter’s currently effective Statement of Rates and Shipper’s Gas Transportation Service Agreement(s). 4. OPERATING PROVISIONS 4.1 To protect the integrity of its LDC Pipeline System or to meet its Firm obligations to other Shippers, Transporter shall have the right to require Shipper to balance its receipts and deliveries at any time, without liability to Transporter. 4.2 Shipper is responsible for obtaining Shipper's Gas, nominating receipts and deliveries, managing Imbalances, and payment of all costs of such gas, and for the transportation of such gas to Transporter's Receipt Point(s) from the Interconnecting Party(s). Shipper shall deliver or cause to be delivered to Transporter at the Receipt Point(s) any gas which Shipper desires to have transported, plus applicable Fuel Reimbursement. Shipper shall also receive or cause to be received gas delivered by Transporter at the Delivery Point(s). 4.3 If Shipper has multiple Gas Transportation Service Agreements with Transporter, Shipper shall not be permitted to combine services available under such Gas Transportation Service Agreements. Specifically, gas shall be received under a particular Gas Transportation Service Agreement and shall be delivered under that same Gas Transportation Service Agreement. 4.4 Transporter may take such action as reasonably necessary to prevent damage to or material deterioration of its LDC Pipeline System and to maintain the operational integrity of the LDC Pipeline System. 5. REQUEST FOR GAS TRANSPORTATION SERVICE 5.1 A Gas Transportation Service Agreement is required for all services hereunder. Any potential Shipper wishing to obtain services from Transporter shall submit in writing to Transporter a request for a Gas Transportation Service Agreement. The potential Shipper shall provide information requested by Transporter if necessary to adequately examine such potential Shipper’s request. A standard request form is provided for this purpose as part this Operating Statement. If Transporter and the potential Shipper mutually agree to the rate(s) that the potential Shipper will pay for transportation service, then Transporter shall, subject to the execution of a Gas Transportation Service Agreement, endeavor to provide service within the time specified in the written request. The potential Shipper's request of a Gas Transportation Service Agreement shall be considered complete only if the information specified in Section 5.2 is provided in writing via U.S. first-class certified mail return receipt requested, overnight courier, E-mail, or hand delivery by an independent third party to the address listed below. Requests should be sent to: Northern States Power Company, a Minnesota corporation Natural Gas Services 414 Nicollet Mall Minneapolis, MN 55401 5.2 Each request for service shall include the following information: (a) Potential Shipper's name, address, representative, telephone number, and e-mail address, if available. (b) Type of service requested: Firm transportation, Interruptible transportation. (c) Receipt Point(s) and Delivery Point(s) for all services, including the MDQ applicable to each point. (d) MDQ, as applicable, for the requested Gas Transportation Service Agreement. (e) Term of Gas Transportation Service Agreement, including the date service is requested to commence and the date service is requested to terminate. (f) 24-hour contact information for Shipper and Point Operator(s) at Shipper’s requested Receipt Point(s) and Delivery Point(s). (g) All credit information required by Transporter. (h) Other requested provisions, such as quality specifications for gas delivered upstream of a processing facility. 5.3 Service requests by potential Shippers for Firm transportation shall be processed on a first-come, first-served basis. That is, capacity for Firm service shall be allocated to the first Shipper with a valid request that contains the acceptable items listed under Section 5.2, subject, however, at all times to Transporter’s satisfactory credit appraisal. 5.4 Transporter shall have the right to reject any request for a Gas Transportation Service Agreement that does not contain the required information set forth herein and shall have no liability to Shipper or any other entity in connection with such rejection. If a Gas Transportation Service Agreement is not fully executed by both Shipper and Transporter within sixty (60) days of the date of Shipper’s request for a Gas Transportation Service Agreement, then the request shall automatically be deemed rejected. Within thirty (30) days of Shipper's receipt of a Gas Transportation Service Agreement from Transporter, Shipper must execute and deliver to Transporter such Gas Transportation Service Agreement. If Transporter has not received an executed Gas Transportation Service Agreement within the required time, Transporter may declare the agreement null and void. 6. NOMINATIONS AND SCHEDULING 6.1 For each Gas Transportation Service Agreement, Shipper shall nominate to Transporter daily quantity requirements requested to be transported by Transporter through the LDC Pipeline System. These quantities shall not exceed Shipper’s MDQ. Nominations and timing of same shall be in accordance with Transporter’s nomination procedures set forth in Shipper’s Gas Transportation Service Agreement, which shall include identification of Receipt Point(s) from which Shipper requests Transporter to receive gas and Delivery Point(s) to which Shipper requests Transporter to deliver gas under the Gas Transportation Service Agreement. Nominations are subject to the approval of Transporter. 6.2 Transporter shall have the right to require Nomination changes to ensure that receipts and deliveries match. When Shipper receives notification of such change in the Nomination, Shipper shall be responsible for informing Interconnecting Party(s) of the change. If the Interconnecting Party(s) does not confirm the Nomination change, further transportation may be curtailed until such confirmation is obtained or another Nomination is confirmed. 6.3 Nomination Changes by Transporter. If, on any Gas Day, Transporter determines that there is an under-delivery or over-delivery of natural gas into or out of the LDC Pipeline System from or to an Interconnecting Party(s), Transporter shall have the right to make or require Shipper to make adjustments to Shipper's Nominations to more accurately reflect actual deliveries of supply into or out of the LDC Pipeline System. 6.4 Transporter will, within a reasonable time, confirm with Interconnecting Party(s) an Interconnecting Party(s)'s curtailment of Shipper's Gas supplies. If a Shipper's gas supplies are curtailed, Transporter will accept changes by the cycle deadline, revised Nominations that conform to the receipt quantities confirmed by Transporter from the curtailed Interconnecting Party(s). Transporter will also allow re-sourcing of curtailed quantities from existing or new Receipt Point(s), provided the revised Nomination is submitted no later than the cycle deadline for the Gas Day. Shipper is responsible to notify the Interconnecting Party(s) to make corresponding confirmations of supply to Transporter no later than the cycle nomination deadline. Any revised Nomination not confirmed by the Interconnecting Party(s) on or before the cycle nomination deadline shall be deemed denied. In no event shall revised Nominations bump quantities already previously scheduled and confirmed for such Gas Day. 6.5 In the event of an emergency, Transporter will accept revised Nominations prior to the cycle deadline that conform to the receipt quantities received by Transporter from the curtailed Interconnecting Party(s). 6.6. Transporter’s Gas Scheduling Department may be contacted by Shipper as follows: Scheduling@xcelenergy.com 7. RECEIPT POINT(S) AND DELIVERY POINT(S) 7.1 Shipper shall tender all gas for transportation on the LDC Pipeline System at the Receipt Point(s) as specified in Shipper’s Gas Transportation Service Agreement. The quantity of gas tendered by Shipper to Transporter at each Receipt Point for transportation shall not exceed the MDQ specified in Shipper’s Gas Transportation Service Agreement, plus Fuel Reimbursement, if applicable, without the prior consent of Transporter. 7.2 Transporter shall tender all gas to be delivered to Shipper at the Delivery Point(s) as specified in Shipper’s Gas Transportation Service Agreement. Transporter shall deliver quantities of gas to Shipper at each Delivery Point up to the MDQ specified in Shipper’s Gas Transportation Service Agreement, unless otherwise agreed to by Transporter. 7.3 Shipper shall be responsible for transportation downstream from the Delivery Point(s) and payment of all transportation charges relating thereto. Shipper shall be responsible for transportation upstream to the Receipt Point(s) and payment of all transportation charges relating thereto. Transporter shall have no liability for any upstream or downstream transportation. 7.4 Any Firm Shipper receiving Firm transportation service shall designate at least one (1) Receipt Point in the Gas Transportation Service Agreement. Transporter will allow amendments to Receipt Point(s) designated in the Gas Transportation Service Agreement. Any Shipper who wishes to amend the Receipt Point(s) identified in its Gas Transportation Service Agreement shall submit a request to Transporter. Transporter shall grant such changes if the capacity is available, and the change can be made without adversely affecting system operations or other Firm obligations at the new or existing Receipt Point(s). Upon its approval of such request, Transporter shall submit an amendment to Shipper and Shipper will execute an amendment to effectuate the change. In no event shall Shipper be entitled to more Transportation Service than is provided for under the Gas Transportation Service Agreement. Nominations for Interruptible transportation service will be honored at such Receipt Point(s) consistent with established priorities. A Shipper may nominate quantities at any Receipt Point(s) up to its MDQ, as applicable. 7.5 Any Firm Shipper receiving Firm transportation service shall designate at least one (1) Delivery Point in the Gas Transportation Service Agreement and shall designate an allocation of its MDQ to each such Delivery Point. Transporter will allow amendments to Delivery Point(s) designated in the Gas Transportation Service Agreement. Any Shipper who wishes to amend the Delivery Point(s) identified in its Gas Transportation Service Agreement shall submit a request to Transporter. Transporter shall grant such changes if the capacity is available, and the change can be made without adversely affecting system operations or other Firm obligations at the new or existing Delivery Point(s). Upon its approval of such request, Transporter shall submit an amendment to Shipper and Shipper will execute such amendment to effectuate the change. In no event shall Shipper be entitled to more transportation service than is provided for under the Gas Transportation Service Agreement. Nominations for Interruptible transportation service will be honored at such Delivery Point(s) consistent with established priorities. A Shipper may nominate quantities at any Delivery Point up to its MDQ, as applicable. 8. PRIORITY OF SERVICE 8.1 From time to time, Transporter may determine, in its reasonable judgment, that it does not have sufficient capacity to accommodate all Nominations for service through a Receipt Point, Delivery Point, or segment of its LDC Pipeline System (“Constrained Point”). In that event, Transporter shall schedule or curtail service using the following priorities. (a) Priority of Firm Transportation Service. Firm transportation service shall have the highest priority on the LDC Pipeline System. In the event Transporter has insufficient capacity on a segment of its LDC Pipeline System to schedule all Nominations for service, Transporter shall allocate the available capacity on the affected segment first among Firm Shippers nominating to Receipt Point(s) upstream of the capacity constraint and Delivery Point(s) downstream of the capacity constraint on a pro rata basis based on each such Shipper’s MDQ. (b) Priority and Scheduling of Interruptible Transportation Service. Interruptible transportation service shall be scheduled when, and to the extent that, in Transporter's reasonable judgment, capacity is available in Transporter's existing facilities after first scheduling all Firm transportation service and considering all LDC Pipeline System operating requirements. Interruptible Shippers paying the maximum rate shall have the highest priority among all Interruptible Shippers. Transporter may, but is not obligated, to provide transportation at a discounted rate, and shall give priority from the least discount to the greatest discount. If two or more Shippers are paying the same rate for Interruptible service and there is insufficient capacity to serve all Shippers paying such rate, Transporter shall provide service pro rata based on the quotient of the quantity nominated by each Shipper at the Constrained Point divided by the total quantity nominated by all such Shippers sharing the priority. 9. CURTAILMENT 9.1 Transporter shall have the right to curtail or interrupt transportation service on any portion of its LDC Pipeline System at any time for reasons of Force Majeure, as defined in Section 17, or when Transporter makes modifications or repairs to or performs maintenance or testing on its LDC Pipeline System. Transporter shall provide notice of such occurrences as is reasonable under the circumstances. 9.2 Any curtailment of service shall be in reverse order of priority as set forth in Section 8 of this Operating Statement. Further, in curtailing Interruptible service, Transporter shall recognize all LDC Pipeline System operating requirements and all qualities of service. 9.3 Transporter shall not be liable for any loss or damage to any person or property caused, in whole or in part, by any Interruption or curtailment of service, except to the extent caused by Transporter's gross negligence or willful misconduct. Shipper agrees to indemnify and hold harmless Transporter, its officers, directors, agents, employees, and contractors of all tiers from and against any and all claims, liabilities, losses, damages, costs and expenses (including, without limitation, attorneys’ fees) whatsoever brought by any person or entity as a result of or arising out of any Interruption or curtailment of service hereunder for Shipper, whether or not caused by Transporter's negligence, but not to the extent caused by Transporter's gross negligence or willful misconduct. 10. BALANCING AND PENALTIES 10.1 Shipper and Transporter agree to balance daily and monthly delivery point nominations with actual daily and monthly deliveries on an ongoing basis. Shipper agrees to exert its best efforts to keep daily deliveries within five (5) percent of daily nominations and to keep monthly nominations equal to monthly actual deliveries. Shipper or Agent shall be responsible for balancing pipeline receipt point nominations made to suppliers and third party transporting pipeline(s) with actual receipt point deliveries. 10.2 Daily Variance Penalty. Shipper will be subject to imbalance penalties when Shipper’s actual daily receipts from Transporter are more than ± 5% Shipper’s daily nomination. The net daily variance will be determined by comparing Shipper’s actual metered use with the volume nominated. The net daily variance will not be subject to an imbalance penalty if Shipper use does not deviate more than ± 5%. If Shipper use deviates more than ± 5%, the net daily variance will be whatever amount is in excess of the ± 5% deviation. The net daily variance will be assessed a penalty of $0.05 per Therm. However, in the event of an operational flow order (OFO), system operation limitation (SOL) or critical day, Shipper’s daily receipts shall be limited to Shipper’s daily nomination. 11. BILLING AND PAYMENT 11.1 Statements and Invoices to Be Rendered. A statement for transportation of Shipper's Gas and an invoice of amounts due Transporter from Shipper for the preceding Month shall be rendered by Transporter to Shipper each Month. Such Monthly statement and invoice shall set forth (i) the charges due for the preceding Month; (ii) the total quantity of gas, stated in Dekatherms, received from and delivered to Shipper hereunder during the preceding Month(s), and the amount due therefore; and if applicable, (iii) information sufficient to explain and support any adjustments made by Transporter in determining the amount billed. If actual quantities are not available, Transporter may invoice Shipper based on the best available data subject to adjustment to actuals at a later date, or Transporter may delay the issuance of the invoice until actual quantities are available. 11.2 Payment and Late Payment Charge. Bills for services provided shall be for a monthly period beginning on the first Gas Day of the Month and are due and payable by Shipper within fourteen (14) Business Days from the date of the bill. Unless otherwise agreed in writing or unless otherwise waived by EBB posting, any amounts in excess of fifty dollars ($50.00) not paid on or before nine (9) Business Days after the due date of the bill may be subject to a late payment charge of 1.5 percent (1.5%) per Month. 11.3 If Shipper gives notice to Transporter’s office prior to the time that payment is due that the correctness of the bill is disputed, stating reasons therefore, Transporter will investigate the dispute. If a dispute arises as to the amount payable in any invoice rendered hereunder, Shipper shall nevertheless pay the amount due under such invoice. Neither such payment nor the acceptance by Transporter of such payment shall be deemed to be a waiver of the right by Shipper to recoup any overpayment, nor shall acceptance of any payment by Transporter be deemed to be a waiver by Transporter of any underpayment. If Shipper's failure to pay the undisputed portion of any invoice rendered hereunder continues after the due date of such invoice, then Transporter, in addition to all other legal remedies available to it, shall have the right and option to suspend further deliveries of gas or terminate service under the Gas Transportation Service Agreement. 11.4 If Shipper withholds payment of any disputed amount as authorized herein, Shipper shall submit to Transporter a written explanation of the dispute and any available supporting documentation. The Parties shall then cooperate in good faith to resolve such dispute as expeditiously as possible. 11.5 Both Transporter and Shipper shall have the right at their own expense to examine and audit at any reasonable time the books, records (including measurement, billing and payment) and charts of the other to the extent necessary to verify the accuracy of any statements or charges made under or pursuant to any of the provisions of Shipper's Gas Transportation Service Agreement. Upon request, Shipper shall also make available to Transporter for audit purposes any relevant records of Interconnecting Parties to which Shipper conveniently has access. A formal audit of accounts shall not be made more often than once each Year. Any inaccuracy will be promptly corrected when discovered; provided, however, that neither Transporter nor Shipper shall be required to maintain books, records or charts for a period of more than twenty-four (24) Months. Neither Transporter nor Shipper shall have any right to question or contest any charge or credit if the matter is not called to the attention of the other in writing within the twenty-four (24) Month period. 12. MEASUREMENT 12.1 Measuring Equipment. Unless otherwise agreed upon, Transporter will install, maintain and operate or cause to be installed, maintained and operated measuring stations equipped with flow meters and other necessary metering and measuring equipment by which quantities of gas received and delivered may be determined. 12.2 Volume Determination. Gas volume determination shall be done by metering which conforms to appropriate industry standards or practices, or by methods as agreed upon by Transporter or the Interconnecting Party owning the metering equipment. 12.3 New Measurement Techniques. If, at any time, a new method or technique is developed with respect to gas measurement or the determination of the factors used in such gas measurement, such new method or technique may be substituted by Transporter. Transporter shall promptly inform all Shippers of any new techniques adopted. 12.4 Calibration and Testing of Meters. The accuracy of all measuring equipment used for determination of all transportation receipts or deliveries under this Operating Statement shall be verified by Transporter and the Interconnecting Party at reasonable intervals and, if requested, in the presence of a representative of Shipper, but neither Shipper nor Transporter shall be required to verify the accuracy of such equipment more frequently than once in a thirty (30)-day period. If either Party at any time desires a special test of any measuring equipment, it will promptly notify the other, and the Parties shall then cooperate to secure a prompt verification of the accuracy of such equipment. Transporter will test the accuracy of its measurement free of charge provided said meter has not been tested within the twelve (12)-Month period immediately prior to such request. 12.5 Correction of Metering Errors. If, upon any test, any measuring equipment is found to be inaccurate, such equipment shall be adjusted immediately to measure accurately. If, upon any test, the measuring equipment is found to be inaccurate by more than two percent (2%), any payments based upon inaccurate measurement shall be corrected at the rate of such inaccuracy for any period which is known definitely or agreed upon, but in case the period is not known definitely or agreed upon, such correction shall be for a period extending over one-half (1/2) of the time elapsed since the date of the last test, not to exceed twenty-four (24) Months. 12.6 Failure of Measuring Equipment. In the event any measuring equipment is out of service or is found registering inaccurately and the error is not determinable by test, or by previous recordings, the quantity of receipts or deliveries through such equipment shall be estimated and agreed to by the Parties upon the first of the following methods which is feasible: (a) By correcting the error if the percentage of error is ascertainable by calibration, special test, or mathematical calculation, or, in the absence of (a); (b) By using the registration of any check meter or meters, if installed and accurately registering, or, in the absence of (a) and (b); (c) By estimating the quantity of gas received or delivered based on receipts or deliveries during preceding periods under similar conditions when the measuring equipment was registering accurately. 12.7 Preservation of Records. Shipper and Transporter shall preserve for a period of at least two (2) years, or for such longer period as may be required by appropriate authority for test data, charts or other similar records. 13. QUANTITY 13.1 Allocation of Receipts and Deliveries. Transporter will use the best information it has available to allocate receipts and deliveries among Shippers. If the quantities received or delivered by Transporter differ from the scheduled receipts or deliveries, respectively, such differences will be allocated to operational balancing agreements between Transporter and the Interconnecting Party(ies). In such cases, Shipper receipts and deliveries will be allocated based upon scheduled receipt and delivery quantities, respectively. In the absence of an operational balancing agreement, the receipts or deliveries will be prorated among Shippers on the basis of the receipts scheduled by Transporter for each Shipper. 13.2 Adjustment of Receipts and Deliveries. It shall be the responsibility of the Shipper to control and, if necessary, adjust deliveries of gas to the Transporter for transportation hereunder and to control, and if necessary, adjust receipts of transportation gas from Transporter, in order to maintain a daily balance of receipts and deliveries. Transporter shall not be obligated to receive or deliver gas on any day in excess of the transportation quantities scheduled by the Transporter, nor shall Transporter be obligated to deliver to Shipper at the Delivery Point(s) transportation quantities in excess of the Equivalent Quantity. Upon notification, Shipper shall be obligated to adjust receipts and deliveries of transportation gas to correct or avoid any Imbalance. Nothing in the Gas Transportation Service Agreement or this Operating Statement shall limit Transporter’s right to take actions as may be required to adjust receipts and deliveries of gas in order to alleviate conditions which threaten the integrity of the LDC Pipeline System. 14. GAS QUALITY All natural gas received by or delivered from Transporter shall meet the quality specifications of the interstate natural gas pipeline delivering such gas to Transporter. 15. TERM Service will be provided for the specified term set forth in each Gas Transportation Service Agreement. Transporter shall have the right to terminate or suspend service pursuant to the terms set forth in the agreement. 16. NOTICES Any notice, request, demand, or statement (“Notice”) regarding a Gas Transportation Service Agreement, except as otherwise expressly provided herein or in the agreement, shall be given in writing by United States mail, overnight delivery service, courier service, or electronic mail (“E-mail”) to the applicable Party at the address specified in the Gas Transportation Service Agreement, or at such other address as a Party may furnish to the other Party in writing. Notice given by U.S. registered mail shall be deemed delivered on the date indicated by U.S. Postal Service “Signature Confirmation™”; by U.S. certified mail, return receipt requested, on the date indicated on the return receipt; by U.S. first class mail, on the second Business Day after mailing or on such earlier Business Day actually received by the receiving Party; by E-mail, when delivery confirmed by “read-receipt” confirmation; or by hand delivery, on the Business Day delivered. 17. CREDITWORTHINESS 17.1 Acceptance of a request for a Gas Transportation Service Agreement, and continued service under any existing Gas Transportation Service Agreement, is conditioned upon a satisfactory credit appraisal of Shipper by Transporter. Transporter shall not be required to perform or to continue any service on behalf of any Shipper who is or has become insolvent; who fails to meet its payment obligations to Transporter; or who is not creditworthy, as defined herein, and does not otherwise provide reasonable security for payment, as described in Section 16.2, below. Eligible security may include cash deposits, an irrevocable standby letter of credit, or parental guaranty in a form and from an issuing entity acceptable to Transporter, or other security acceptable to Transporter. Any unsecured credit offered to Shipper will be based on Transporter’s review of Shipper’s financial statements, senior unsecured long-term debt (un-enhanced by third party support), any third party credit ratings (e.g., Moody’s, Standard & Poor's/S&P, or Fitch), recent payment history, and/or other information relating to Shipper’s creditworthiness. If Transporter believes, in its reasonable judgment after review of Shipper’s and/or Shipper’s Credit Support Provider’s financial statements and/or any and all other information available, that Shipper will fully, timely and faithfully perform all obligations under all its Gas Transportation Service Agreements and/or that Shipper’s Credit Support Provider’s Guarantee fully secures such obligations and is enforceable by Transporter against such Credit Support Provider and that such Credit Support Provider will fully, timely and faithfully perform under such Guarantee. Shipper grants to Transporter a first priority, continuing security interest in, lien on and right of set-off against all security provided hereunder. Any security required hereunder shall not be considered as advance payment or partial payment of any bill for service, but as a prerequisite for service, or continued service, and shall not be transferable to another Shipper. Transporter may apply the security against unpaid Shipper bills for service received only in the event service for the account on which the security was being held is discontinued or otherwise terminated. 17.2 If reasonable grounds for insecurity arise as to the creditworthiness of Shipper at any time during the term of the Gas Transportation Service Agreement, Transporter may require, as a condition to continued performance under the Gas Transportation Service Agreement, that Shipper provide reasonable security in an amount, as determined by Transporter on a not unduly discriminatory basis, not to exceed the sum of the applicable gas transportation charges for the highest three (3) months of estimated deliveries. However, in instances where such service requires the development of new facilities or expansion of the system, Transporter may require additional credit assurance based on the projected cost of such new facilities or expansion capacity. Additional security may also be required from an existing Shipper if Transporter reasonably determines that changes in the Shipper's financial condition or an increase in Shipper’s gas transportation business with Transporter warrants such increase. Eligible security may include: (a) a cash payment (in U.S. dollars), as collateral held for security (Shipper hereby grants Transporter a first priority security interest in any such cash); (b) an irrevocable standby letter of credit from an issuing entity acceptable to Transporter and in a form acceptable to Transporter; (c) a Guaranty; or (d) any combination of (a), (b) and (c) above. 17.3 Transporter may reassess the creditworthiness of and performance by any Shipper, at any time and from time to time, and Shipper shall be required to demonstrate creditworthiness and/or provide adequate security and assurances of performance throughout the term of the executed Gas Transportation Service Agreement. Additional security may be required from an existing Shipper if Transporter reasonably determines that changes in the Shipper's financial condition or an increase in Shipper’s gas transportation business with Transporter warrants. Such determination will be based on Transporter’s review of financial statements, senior unsecured long-term debt (un-enhanced by third party support), rating(s) from credit reporting agency(ies), recent payment history, and/or other information relating to Shipper’s creditworthiness. Transporter may require Shipper to provide additional security up to an amount such that the total amount of Shipper’s security does not exceed the sum of the applicable gas transportation charges for the highest three (3) months’ actual deliveries, plus three (3) times the highest Month’s under-delivery Imbalance cashout charges incurred during the preceding twelve (12)-Month period. 17.4 Shipper grants to Transporter a first priority continuing security interest in, a lien on and a right of set-off against all provided security hereunder. Any security required hereunder shall not be considered as advance payment or partial payment of any bill for service, but as a prerequisite for service, or continued service and shall not be transferable to another Shipper. The security may be used by Transporter for payment of service to be applied against unpaid bills only in the event service for the account on which the security was being held is discontinued or otherwise terminated. 17.5 For purposes herein, the insolvency of a Shipper shall be conclusively demonstrated if such Shipper or any parent entity thereof makes an assignment or any general arrangement for the benefit of creditors; files a petition or otherwise commences, authorizes or acquiesces in the commencement of a proceeding or cause under any bankruptcy or similar law for the petition of creditors or has such petition filed against it and such proceeding remains undismissed for thirty (30) days; otherwise becomes bankrupt or insolvent (however evidenced); liquidates a substantial part of its property or affairs; or is generally unable to pay its debts as they become due. 17.6 Refunds of Deposits for Gas Transportation Service. Refunds to Shippers of deposits will be made when service is terminated and all outstanding bills have been paid. Interest will be paid on Shipper deposits either in cash or by a credit to the Shipper's account. Interest will be paid upon refund of the deposit or annually upon request of a Shipper. The interest rate shall be equal to the three-month treasury bill rate as published monthly by the Federal Reserve Board. 17.7 If either Party (for purposes herein, the "Delinquent Party") fails to pay in full any amount owing to the other Party (the "Unpaid Party") under any Gas Transportation Service Agreement within fourteen (14) Business Days after such amount becomes due, then in addition to all other remedies available to the Unpaid Party under the Gas Transportation Service Agreement, at law or in equity, the Unpaid Party may set off the overdue amount against amounts owed by the Unpaid Party to the Delinquent Party under the Gas Transportation Service Agreement or any other agreement between the Parties. 18. FORCE MAJEURE 18.1 Force Majeure shall mean circumstances not within the control of the Parties and which by the exercise of due diligence, the affected Party is unable to overcome. Force Majeure shall include but not be limited to acts of God; strikes, lockouts and industrial disputes or disturbances; inability to secure or delays in obtaining labor, materials, supplies, permits, easements or rights-of-way grants, including, without limitation, inability to secure materials by reason of allocations promulgated by authorized governmental agencies; arrests and restraints of governments and people; interruptions by government or court orders; present and future valid orders, decisions or rulings of any government or regulatory entity having or alleging proper jurisdiction; acts of the public enemy; vandalism; wars; riots; civil disturbances; acts of terrorism; blockades; insurrections; epidemics; landslides; lightning; tornadoes, hurricanes; earthquakes; fires; storms; floods; washouts; explosions; breakage and/or accidents to facilities including, without limitation, machinery, lines of pipe, wells or subsurface storage caverns or reservoirs; outages or shutdowns of power plant equipment or lines of pipe for inspection, maintenance or repairs to machinery, equipment, lines of pipe or other facilities; freezing of equipment, lines of pipe and partial or entire failure of wells or other facilities; inability to obtain or unavoidable delay in obtaining material, equipment, right-of-way or other permits; and any other cause, whether of the kind enumerated herein or otherwise, not reasonably within the control of Transporter or Shipper and which by the exercise of due diligence such Party is unable to prevent or overcome. 18.2 The Force Majeure provisions shall not apply to the inability of Transporter to accept gas at the Receipt Point(s) or deliver gas at the Delivery Point(s) nominated by Shipper for the purpose of correcting or curing an Imbalance in Shipper's Gas transported on the LDC Pipeline System. A Force Majeure event shall not relieve Shipper from its obligations to make payments when due, including the payments of Firm Capacity Reservation Charges for the duration of such cause, except as may otherwise be provided in the Gas Transportation Service Agreement. 18.3 If either Party shall fail to perform any obligation imposed upon it by this Operating Statement or by an executed Gas Transportation Service Agreement, and such failure shall be caused, or contributed to, by Force Majeure as described in Section 17.1 above, such failure shall be deemed not to be a breach of the obligation of such Party, but such Party shall use due diligence to carry out its obligations; provided, however, that no such cause affecting the performance of a Party shall continue to relieve such Party from its obligation after the expiration of a reasonable period-of-time within which by the use of commercially reasonable diligence such Party could have remedied the situation preventing its performance, nor shall any such cause relieve either Party from any obligation unless such Party shall give notice thereof in writing to the other Party with reasonable promptness; and like notice shall be given upon termination of such cause. The obligations of the Parties, other than to make payments of amounts due hereunder, so far as they are affected by such Force Majeure, shall be suspended during the continuance of any inability so caused, but for no longer period. 18.4 It is understood and agreed that the settlement of strikes or lockouts shall be entirely within the discretion of the Party having the difficulty, and that the above requirement that any Force Majeure shall be remedied with all reasonable dispatch shall not require the settlement of strikes or lockouts by acceding to the demands of the opposing Party when such course is inadvisable in the discretion of the Party having the difficulty. 19. TITLE AND RISK OF LOSS 19.1 Shipper warrants for itself, its successors, and assigns, that it will have good title to all gas delivered to Transporter under Shipper's Gas Transportation Service Agreement and, further, that such gas shall be free and clear of all liens, encumbrances, and adverse claims of every kind and, further, that it will indemnify and hold Transporter and its affiliates, and its and their officers, directors, agents, and employees, harmless from and against any and all claims, liabilities, losses, damages, liens, and encumbrances, and costs and expenses (including, without limitation, attorneys’ fees) arising directly or indirectly from or with respect to the title to gas tendered by or on behalf of Shipper to Transporter under any Gas Transportation Service Agreement. 19.2 Transporter shall be deemed to be in possession and control of the gas delivered by Shipper upon and after Transporter's receipt and acceptance of such gas after it passes the inlet flange at the Receipt Point(s) and until the redelivered gas passes the outlet flange at the Delivery Point(s) for delivery to or for the account of Shipper. As between Shipper and Transporter: (i) during Transporter’s possession and control of the gas, Transporter shall be responsible for all damages, losses, or injuries caused thereby, except for damages, losses, or injuries arising or resulting from the negligence or willful misconduct of Shipper; and (ii) Shipper shall be deemed to be in possession and control of such gas at all other times (Transporter having no responsibility with respect to the gas before receipt at the Receipt Point(s) or after delivery at the Delivery Point(s)) and Shipper shall be responsible for all damages, losses or injuries other than those for which Transporter has assumed responsibility, as stated herein. 19.3 Notwithstanding the foregoing, title to all gas delivered by Shipper to Transporter in accordance with Shipper's Gas Transportation Service Agreement will remain with Shipper during transport by Transporter; provided, however, it is understood and agreed that the gas delivered at the Delivery Point(s) will not be the identical gas that was delivered to Transporter for transportation hereunder, but such gas will be a part of the commingled delivery of gas and, for the purpose of Shipper's Gas Transportation Service Agreement, the commingled gas may be substituted for Shipper's Gas on a heat-equivalent basis. 20. INDEMNIFICATION AND LIMITATION OF LIABILITY 20.1 Shipper agrees to indemnify and hold Transporter, its officers, directors, agents, employees, and contractors of all tiers, harmless from and against all claims, liabilities, losses, damages, liens and encumbrances, and costs and expenses (including, without limitation, attorneys’ fees) related to, arising from or with respect to the gas transported in accordance with Shipper’s Gas Transportation Service Agreement or the Interruption or curtailment of such transportation service, as provided for herein, or the breach by Shipper of any representation or warranty; provided, however, Shipper shall not be liable for the negligence or willful misconduct of Transporter. This general indemnity shall apply only to the extent the subject matter is not otherwise subject to a specific indemnity set out elsewhere in this Operating Statement. 20.2 NOTWITHSTANDING ANY OTHER PROVISION HEREIN OR IN ANY GAS TRANSPORTATION SERVICE AGREEMENT, TRANSPORTER’S AND SHIPPER’S LIABILITY TO EACH OTHER SHALL, IN ADDITION TO ANY OTHER LIMITATIONS SET FORTH IN THESE TERMS AND CONDITIONS, BE LIMITED TO DIRECT ACTUAL DAMAGES ONLY. SUCH DIRECT ACTUAL DAMAGES SHALL BE THE SOLE AND EXCLUSIVE REMEDY UNDER ANY GAS TRANSPORTATION SERVICE AGREEMENT, AND ALL OTHER REMEDIES OR DAMAGES AT LAW OR IN EQUITY ARE WAIVED. IN NO EVENT SHALL TRANSPORTER OR SHIPPER BE LIABLE TO THE OTHER PARTY FOR INCIDENTAL, CONSEQUENTIAL, SPECIAL, OR PUNITIVE DAMAGES, REGARDLESS OF THE SOLE, JOINT, CONCURRENT, ACTIVE, PASSIVE, OR GROSS NEGLIGENCE, FAULT OR STRICT LIABILITY OF THE PARTY RELIEVED OF RESPONSIBILITY FOR SUCH DAMAGES UNDER THIS PROVISION. 21. ASSIGNMENT The Gas Transportation Service Agreement between Shipper and Transporter, including, without limitation, each indemnification, shall inure to and bind each respective Party's permitted successors and assigns. Shipper shall not transfer or assign any Gas Transportation Service Agreement without the prior written approval of Transporter, given in Transporter's reasonable judgment, taking into account, inter alia, the creditworthiness of the proposed assignee. Notwithstanding anything else herein which may be construed to the contrary, any discount in rate provided for in a Gas Transportation Service Agreement or in any supplemental discount rate agreement associated with a Gas Transportation Service Agreement shall be deemed null and void upon Shipper's transfer or assignment of such Gas Transportation Service Agreement, except when such transfer or assignment is to an affiliate, as described in the following sentence. Notwithstanding the foregoing, either Shipper or Transporter may transfer its interest to any affiliate by assignment, merger or otherwise without the prior approval of the other Party, but no such transfer shall operate to relieve the transferor of its obligations hereunder. Additionally, notwithstanding any of the foregoing, either Party may assign its right, title, and interest in a Gas Transportation Service Agreement, including any and all extensions, renewals, amendments, and supplements thereto, to a trustee or trustees, individual or corporate, as security for bonds or other obligations or securities, without such trustee or trustees assuming or becoming in any respect obligated to perform any of the obligations of the assignor and, if any such trustee be a corporation, without its being required to qualify to do business in the state in which the performance of the subject Gas Transportation Service Agreement may occur. Shipper or Transporter's transfer in violation of this Section 20 shall be void or voidable at the election of the other Party. 22. LAWS AND REGULATIONS 22.1 Transporter's transportation services are subject to all present and future valid laws and lawful orders of all regulatory authorities now or hereafter having jurisdiction over the services or facilities used to provide such services. Should Shipper or Transporter, by force of any such law or regulation imposed at any time during the term of Shipper’s Gas Transportation Service Agreement, be rendered unable, wholly or in part, to carry out its obligations under the Gas Transportation Service Agreement, other than to make payments due hereunder, the Gas Transportation Service Agreement nevertheless shall continue and shall be deemed modified to conform with the requirements of such law or regulation, except as hereinafter provided. 22.2 The Gas Transportation Service Agreement shall be modified to the least extent necessary to conform to such requirements; the primary intent of any such modification being to retain, to the greatest extent possible, the bargain of the Parties under the Gas Transportation Service Agreement. The Gas Transportation Service Agreement is expressly made subject to any and all tariff and other rate filings made by Transporter and approved by any federal or state regulatory body as such may be amended from time to time. Transporter shall have the right to propose to the FERC, North Dakota PSC, or other governing regulatory body such changes in its rates and terms of service at any time as it deems necessary. Furthermore, the Gas Transportation Service Agreement shall be deemed to include any changes which are made effective pursuant to order or regulation or provisions of law, without prejudice to Shipper's right to protest the same. In the event that any regulatory body, having jurisdiction over the Gas Transportation Service Agreement, prohibits Transporter from collecting specific rates for the services provided under the Gas Transportation Service Agreement or subjects its transportation facilities to any greater or different regulation or jurisdiction, by order or otherwise, than that existing on the date of initial transportation service hereunder (or thereafter, as such regulation or jurisdiction may have changed and been accepted), then Transporter shall have the right to terminate the Gas Transportation Service Agreement on the effective date of such greater or different regulation or jurisdiction, anything herein to the contrary notwithstanding and shall have no liability to Shipper or any other entity in connection with any such termination. 23. TAXES AND GOVERNMENTAL FEES Shipper shall be liable for and shall pay, cause to be paid, or reimburse Transporter if Transporter has paid, causes to be paid or becomes obligated to pay, any Taxes or Governmental Fees attributable to or associated with any or all of the following: (i) any service or transaction to be performed by Transporter or its designee under this Agreement, and (ii) any payment by Transporter or its designee to Shipper or Shipper's designee under this Agreement. The provisions of this Section shall survive termination of this Agreement. "Taxes" means any or all ad valorem, property, occupation, severance, production, extraction, first use, conservation, Btu or energy, gathering, transport, pipeline, utility, gross receipts, gas or oil revenue, gas or oil import, privilege, sales, use, consumption, excise, lease, transaction, and other taxes or New Taxes, governmental charges or fees, licenses, fees, permits and assessments, or increases therein, and any interest or penalties on such taxes, charges, licenses, fees, permits, New Taxes and assessments, other than taxes based on net income or net worth and Governmental Fees. "New Taxes" means (i) any Taxes enacted and effective after the effective date of this Operating Statement, including, without limitation, that portion of any Taxes or New Taxes that constitutes an increase, or (ii) any law, order, rule or regulation, or interpretation thereof, enacted and effective after such effective date resulting in the application of any Taxes to a new or different class of parties. "Governmental Fees" means any and all privilege, franchise fees, charges, user fees or rentals levied by governmental entities in exchange for the grant of privileges relating to use of land or improvements thereon. 24. WAIVERS No waiver by Transporter or Shipper of any one (1) or more defaults in the performance of any provision hereunder shall operate or be construed as a waiver of any future default or defaults, whether of a like or a different character. No delay by Transporter in enforcing any of its rights may be deemed a waiver of such rights.
